<para id="eip-734">In the <link class="phetsim" window="new" url="http://phet.colorado.edu/sims/ideal-gas/gas-properties_en.jnlp">simulation</link> you can verify Charle's law by holding the pressure constant and seeing what happens as you vary the volume and temperature.</para><exercise id="secfhsst_id755"><title> Charles's Law 1 </title>
      <problem id="probfhsst_id756">
      <para id="id235332">Ammonium chloride and calcium hydroxide are allowed to react. The ammonia that is released in the reaction is collected in a gas syringe and sealed in. This gas is allowed to come to room temperature which is 32<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>∘</m:mo></m:msup></m:math>C. The volume of the ammonia is found to be 122 ml. It is now placed in a water bath set at 7<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>∘</m:mo></m:msup></m:math>C. What will be the volume reading after the syringe has been left in the bath for a some time (e.g. 1 hour) (assume the plunger moves completely freely)?</para>
      
      </problem>
      <solution id="solfhsst_id760"> <list id="listfhsst_id760" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" class="stepwise">
      
      
      <item> <label> Write down all the information that you know about the gas. </label>
      <para id="id235408">V<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = 122 ml and V<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = ?</para>
      <para id="id235438">T<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = 32<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>∘</m:mo></m:msup></m:math>C and T<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = 7<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mo>∘</m:mo></m:msup></m:math>C</para>
      </item> <item> <label> Convert the known values to SI units if necessary. </label>
      <para id="id235498">Here, temperature must be converted into Kelvin, therefore:</para>
      <para id="id235502">T<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = 32 + 273 = 305 K</para>
      <para id="id235518">T<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mrow/><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:math> = 7 + 273 = 280 K</para>
      </item> <item> <label> Choose a relevant gas law equation that will allow you to calculate the unknown variable. </label>
      <equation id="id235539">
        <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mfrac>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mi>V</m:mi>
                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
              </m:msub>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mi>T</m:mi>
                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
              </m:msub>
            </m:mfrac>
            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
            <m:mfrac>
